When you read a file and store the lines as a String object, the encoding is converted to the internal representation of String (UTF-16). `lineTxt.getBytes()` converts the UTF-16 String to a byte array in your platform&#39;s default encoding (It&#39;s depends on the system locale when you&#39;re on Windows. It would be UTF-8 when you&#39;re on the other platform).

If you want to get the content of the file to a byte array (get the GBK representation and don&#39;t want to convert the content to UTF-16), read the file like this:
```java
try {
    File file = new File(&quot;C:\\tmp\\fileGBK.txt&quot;);
    byte[] lineTxt = Files.readAllBytes(file.toPath());
    System.out.println(Arrays.toString(lineTxt));
} catch (IOException e) {
    e.printStackTrace();
}
```
You will get the representation of the string in GBK (`[-54, -28, -77, -10, -41, ...`).

If you want to read lines from the file one by one and get the GBK representation of the lines:
